From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Charles Kerr <charles@charleskerr.com>
Date: Sat, 16 May 2026 17:12:29 -0500
Subject: fix: preserve node symbols and vtables under thinlto

Electron's official macOS builds enable ThinLTO with whole-program
vtables (-fwhole-program-vtables implies -fsplit-lto-unit). Under this
configuration, Mach-O LTO localizes weak (linkonce_odr/weak_odr)
unnamed_addr vtables during LTO code generation even when other LTO
partitions still reference them, producing undefined-symbol errors at
link time:

  ld64.lld: error: undefined symbol: vtable for
      node::StaticExternalByteResource<unsigned char, char,
      v8::String::ExternalOneByteStringResource>

Three classes of fixes, all of which give the affected symbols strong
(non-discardable, non-localizable) linkage:

1. N-API entry points: mark with __attribute__((used)) so ThinLTO does
   not strip them when no Node.js source references them directly,
   following https://github.com/nodejs/node/pull/49037 .

2. Non-template classes whose virtuals are all inline
   (MemoryRetainerNode, JSGraphJSNode): move one virtual out of line.
   This gives the class a key function, so its vtable is emitted as a
   strong symbol in that translation unit.

3. Class template instantiations (StaticExternalByteResource<...>,
   NgRcBufPointer<Http2RcBufferPointerTraits>::External): these always
   have weak vtables per the Itanium C++ ABI, and no linker option
   prevents Mach-O LTO from localizing them. Add explicit
   specializations for the instantiations node actually uses; an
   explicit specialization is an ordinary class that can have a key
   function (an out-of-line destructor), giving it a strong vtable.
   The specialization bodies are identical to the primary templates,
   and the primary templates and their users are unchanged.

Observed on macOS arm64 official builds; latent on Linux/Windows.

